[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Given a description of a video, generate a video that matches the description.
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Based on long-standing trends in the field, it is possible to extrapolate future directions of NLP.
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Most higher-level NLP applications involve aspects that emulate intelligent behavior and apparent comprehension of natural language.
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] More broadly speaking, the technical operationalization of increasingly advanced aspects of cognitive behavior represents one of the developmental trajectories of NLP(see trends among CoNLL shared tasks above).
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognition refers to "the mental action or process of acquiring knowledge and understanding through thought, experience, and the senses." Cognitive science is the interdisciplinary, scientific study of the mind and its processes.
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Cognitive linguistics is an interdisciplinary branch of linguistics, combining knowledge and research from both psychology and linguistics.
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Especially during the age of symbolic NLP, the area of computational linguistics maintained strong ties with cognitive studies.
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Assign relative measures of meaning to a word, phrase, sentence or piece of text based on the information presented before and after the piece of text being analyzed, e.g., by means of a probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG).
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] Ties with cognitive linguistics are part of the historical heritage of NLP, but they have been less frequently addressed since the statistical turn during the 1990s.
[src:question-answering-nlp/natural-language-processing] More recently, ideas of cognitive NLP have been revived as an approach to achieve explainability, e.g., under the notion of "cognitive AI".
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] A question-answering implementation, usually a computer program, may construct its answers by querying a structured database of knowledge or information, usually a knowledge base.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] More commonly, question-answering systems can pull answers from an unstructured collection of natural language documents.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Some examples of natural language document collections used for question answering systems include reference texts, compiled newswire reports, Wikipedia pages and other World Wide Web pages.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Two early question answering systems were BASEBALL and LUNAR.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] BASEBALL answered questions about Major League Baseball over a period of one year.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] LUNAR answered questions about the geological analysis of rocks returned by the Apollo Moon missions.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Both question answering systems were very effective in their chosen domains.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] LUNAR was demonstrated at a lunar science convention in 1971 and it was able to answer 90% of the questions in its domain that were posed by people untrained on the system.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Further restricted-domain question answering systems were developed in the following years.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The common feature of all these systems is that they had a core database or knowledge system that was hand-written by experts of the chosen domain.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The language abilities of BASEBALL and LUNAR used techniques similar to ELIZA and DOCTOR, the first chatterbot programs.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] SHRDLU was a successful question-answering program developed by Terry Winograd in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] It simulated the operation of a robot in a toy world (the "blocks world"), and it offered the possibility of asking the robot questions about the state of the world.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The strength of this system was the choice of a very specific domain and a very simple world with rules of physics that were easy to encode in a computer program.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] In the 1970s, knowledge bases were developed that targeted narrower domains of knowledge.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The question answering systems developed to interface with these expert systems produced more repeatable and valid responses to questions within an area of knowledge.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] These expert systems closely resembled modern question answering systems except in their internal architecture.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Expert systems rely heavily on expert-constructed and organized knowledge bases, whereas many modern question answering systems rely on statistical processing of a large, unstructured, natural language text corpus.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The 1970s and 1980s saw the development of comprehensive theories in computational linguistics, which led to the development of ambitious projects in text comprehension and question answering.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] One example was the Unix Consultant (UC), developed by Robert Wilensky at U.C.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The system answered questions pertaining to the Unix operating system.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] It had a comprehensive, hand-crafted knowledge base of its domain, and it aimed at phrasing the answer to accommodate various types of users.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Another project was LILOG, a text-understanding system that operated on the domain of tourism information in a German city.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The systems developed in the UC and LILOG projects never went past the stage of simple demonstrations, but they helped the development of theories on computational linguistics and reasoning.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Specialized natural-language question answering systems have been developed, such as EAGLi for health and life scientists.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] In 2011, Watson, a question answering computer system developed by IBM, competed in two exhibition matches of *Jeopardy!* against Brad Rutter and Ken Jennings, winning by a significant margin.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Facebook Research made their DrQA system available under an open source license.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] This system uses Wikipedia as knowledge source.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The open source framework Haystack by deepset combines open-domain question answering with generative question answering and supports the domain adaptation of the underlying language models for industry use cases.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Large Language Models (LLMs)[36] like GPT-4[37], Gemini[38] are examples of successful QA systems that are enabling more sophisticated understanding and generation of text.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] When coupled with Multimodal[39] QA Systems, which can process and understand information from various modalities like text, images, and audio, LLMs significantly improve the capabilities of QA systems.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Question-answering research attempts to develop ways of answering a wide range of question types, including fact, list, definition, how, why, hypothetical, semantically constrained, and cross-lingual questions.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Another way to categorize question-answering systems is by the technical approach used.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Rule-based systems use a set of rules to determine the correct answer to a question.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Statistical systems use statistical methods to find the most likely answer to a question.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Hybrid systems use a combination of rule-based and statistical methods.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] As of 2001, question-answering systems typically included a *question classifier* module that determined the type of question and the type of answer.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Different types of question-answering systems employ different architectures.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] For example, modern open-domain question answering systems may use a retriever-reader architecture.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The retriever is aimed at retrieving relevant documents related to a given question, while the reader is used to infer the answer from the retrieved documents.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Systems such as GPT-3, T5, and BART use an end-to-end architecture in which a transformer-based architecture stores large-scale textual data in the underlying parameters.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Such models can answer questions without accessing any external knowledge sources.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Question answering is dependent on a good search corpus; without documents containing the answer, there is little any question answering system can do.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Larger collections generally mean better question answering performance, unless the question domain is orthogonal to the collection.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Correct answers can be filtered from false positives because the system can rely on versions of the correct answer appearing more times in the corpus than incorrect ones.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Some question answering systems rely heavily on automated reasoning.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] In information retrieval, an open-domain question answering system tries to return an answer in response to the user's question.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The returned answer is in the form of short texts rather than a list of relevant documents.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The system finds answers by using a combination of techniques from computational linguistics, information retrieval, and knowledge representation.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The system takes a natural language question as an input rather than a set of keywords, for example: "When is the national day of China?" It then transforms this input sentence into a query in its logical form.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Accepting natural language questions makes the system more user-friendly, but harder to implement, as there are a variety of question types and the system will have to identify the correct one in order to give a sensible answer.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Assigning a question type to the question is a crucial task; the entire answer extraction process relies on finding the correct question type and hence the correct answer type.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Keyword extraction is the first step in identifying the input question type.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] In some cases, words clearly indicate the question type, e.g., "Who", "Where", "When", or "How many"—these words might suggest to the system that the answers should be of type "Person", "Location", "Date", or "Number", respectively.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] POS (part-of-speech) tagging and syntactic parsing techniques can also determine the answer type.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] In the example above, the subject is "Chinese National Day", the predicate is "is" and the adverbial modifier is "when", therefore the answer type is "Date".
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Unfortunately, some interrogative words like "Which", "What", or "How" do not correspond to unambiguous answer types: Each can represent more than one type.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] In situations like this, other words in the question need to be considered.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] A lexical dictionary such as WordNet can be used for understanding the context.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Once the system identifies the question type, it uses an information retrieval system to find a set of documents that contain the correct keywords.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] A tagger and NP/Verb Group chunker can verify whether the correct entities and relations are mentioned in the found documents.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] For questions such as "Who" or "Where", a named-entity recogniser finds relevant "Person" and "Location" names from the retrieved documents.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Only the relevant paragraphs are selected for ranking.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] A vector space model can classify the candidate answers.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Check if the answer is of the correct type as determined in the question type analysis stage.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] An inference technique can validate the candidate answers.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] A score is then given to each of these candidates according to the number of question words it contains and how close these words are to the candidate—the more and the closer the better.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The answer is then translated by parsing into a compact and meaningful representation.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] An open-source, math-aware, question answering system called MathQA, based on Ask Platypus and Wikidata, was published in 2018.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] MathQA takes an English or Hindi natural language question as input and returns a mathematical formula retrieved from Wikidata as a succinct answer, translated into a computable form that allows the user to insert values for the variables.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The system retrieves names and values of variables and common constants from Wikidata if those are available.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] It is claimed that the system outperforms a commercial computational mathematical knowledge engine on a test set.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] MathQA is hosted by Wikimedia at https://mathqa.wmflabs.org/.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] In 2022, it was extended to answer 15 math question types.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] MathQA methods need to combine natural and formula language.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] One possible approach is to perform supervised annotation via Entity Linking.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The "ARQMath Task" at CLEF 2020 was launched to address the problem of linking newly posted questions from the platform Math Stack Exchange to existing ones that were already answered by the community.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Providing hyperlinks to already answered, semantically related questions helps users to get answers earlier but is a challenging problem because semantic relatedness is not trivial.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The lab was motivated by the fact that 20% of mathematical queries in general-purpose search engines are expressed as well-formed questions.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The challenge contained two separate sub-tasks.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Task 1: "Answer retrieval" matching old post answers to newly posed questions, and Task 2: "Formula retrieval" matching old post formulae to new questions.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Starting with the domain of mathematics, which involves formula language, the goal is to later extend the task to other domains (e.g., STEM disciplines, such as chemistry, biology, etc.), which employ other types of special notation (e.g., chemical formulae).
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The inverse of mathematical question answering—mathematical question generation—has also been researched.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The PhysWikiQuiz physics question generation and test engine retrieves mathematical formulae from Wikidata together with semantic information about their constituting identifiers (names and values of variables).
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] The formulae are then rearranged to generate a set of formula variants.
[src:question-answering-nlp/question-answering] Subsequently, the variables are substituted with random values to generate a large number of different questions suitable for individual student tests.
[src:question-answering-nlp/semantic-search] Some authors regard semantic search as a set of techniques for retrieving knowledge from richly structured data sources like ontologies and XML as found on the Semantic Web.
[src:question-answering-nlp/semantic-search] Such technologies enable the formal articulation of domain knowledge at a high level of expressiveness and could enable the user to specify their intent in more detail at query time.
[src:question-answering-nlp/semantic-search] The articulation enhances content relevance and depth by including specific places, people, or concepts relevant to the query.
[src:question-answering-nlp/semantic-search] Tools like Google's Knowledge Graph provide structured relationships between entities to enrich query interpretation.
[src:question-answering-nlp/semantic-search] Models like BERT and Sentence-BERT convert words or sentences into dense vectors for similarity comparison.
[src:question-answering-nlp/semantic-search] Semantic ontologies like Web Ontology Language, Resource Description Framework, and Schema.org organize concepts and relationships, allowing systems to infer related terms and deeper meanings.
[src:question-answering-nlp/semantic-search] Hybrid search models combine lexical retrieval (e.g., BM25) with semantic ranking using pretrained transformer models for optimal performance.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] In linguistics and natural language processing, a **corpus** (pl.: **corpora**) or **text corpus** is a dataset, consisting of natively digital and older, digitalized, language resources, either annotated or unannotated.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] Annotated, they have been used in corpus linguistics for statistical hypothesis testing, checking occurrences or validating linguistic rules within a specific language territory.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] A corpus may contain texts in a single language (*monolingual corpus*) or text data in multiple languages (*multilingual corpus*).
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] In order to make the corpora more useful for doing linguistic research, they are often subjected to a process known as annotation.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] An example of annotating a corpus is part-of-speech tagging, or *POS-tagging*, in which information about each word's part of speech (verb, noun, adjective, etc.) is added to the corpus in the form of *tags*.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] Another example is indicating the lemma (base) form of each word.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] When the language of the corpus is not a working language of the researchers who use it, interlinear glossing is used to make the annotation bilingual.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] Some corpora have further *structured* levels of analysis applied.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] In particular, smaller corpora may be fully parsed.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] Such corpora are usually called Treebanks or Parsed Corpora.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] The difficulty of ensuring that the entire corpus is completely and consistently annotated means that these corpora are usually smaller, containing around one to three million words.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] Other levels of linguistic structured analysis are possible, including annotations for morphology, semantics and pragmatics.
[src:question-answering-nlp/text-corpus] Corpora are the main knowledge base in corpus linguistics.
